<paragraph blockId="25.[136,458,810,832]" box="[136,458,810,832]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,194,810,831]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<typeStatus box="[136,190,810,831]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Type</typeStatus>
:
</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authority="Cabrera" box="[218,458,810,832]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Huarpea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis box="[218,377,810,832]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Huarpea andina</emphasis>
Cabrera
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,878,1949]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis box="[136,404,878,904]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Rhizomatous subshrubs</emphasis>
, up to 
<quantity box="[490,568,878,905]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" unit="cm" value="4.5">4.5 cm</quantity>
tall, unarmed; underground system formed by thickened rhizomatous stems, occurring at ground level and below. 
<emphasis box="[554,619,915,941]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Stems</emphasis>
erect, single- to much-branched, lenticelate, cylindrical, scales imbricated at base, tomentose. 
<emphasis box="[364,442,951,976]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Leaves</emphasis>
alternate, subrosulate, sessile, persistent, blade linear, coriaceous, lustrous, adaxial face glabrous, abaxial lanate, base truncate, margin revolute, ciliate, apex spiny, venation hyphodromous. 
<emphasis box="[1280,1451,986,1012]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Capitulescence</emphasis>
terminal, monocephalous. 
<emphasis box="[447,545,1022,1048]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Capitula</emphasis>
6-flowered, heterogamous, radiate, sessile, hidden by the leaves, involucre cylindrical–campanulate, 5–7-seriate, phyllaries coriaceous, lanceolate, erect, lanate, apex spiny, margin flat, ciliate. 
<emphasis box="[136,259,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Receptacle</emphasis>
flat, pilose. 
<emphasis box="[402,494,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Flowers</emphasis>
dimorphic. 
<emphasis box="[633,767,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Ray flowers</emphasis>
5, bisexual, subbilabiate (4+1), 5-lobed, with the inner lobe shorter than the outer lobes, externally hirsute-sericeous, white, internally glabrous, yellow. 
<emphasis box="[1213,1347,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Disc flower</emphasis>
1, male, tubular (5+0), externally sericeous-pilose, pistil not seen. 
<emphasis box="[779,866,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Anthers</emphasis>
5, apical appendage lanceolate to obtuse, inserted at the throat of the corolla (ray flowers) or inserted between the base and the throat (disc flowers), filaments free, glabrous. 
<emphasis box="[136,190,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Style</emphasis>
cylindrical, yellow (ray flowers), not seen in disc flowers; 
<emphasis box="[864,967,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Cypselae</emphasis>
turbinate (ray flowers) or cylindrical (disc flowers), densely villous. 
<taxonomicName box="[422,506,1275,1300]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Pappus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[422,506,1275,1300]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Pappus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
plumose or single villous bristle or absent, equal to the corolla length. 
<emphasis box="[1283,1356,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Pollen</emphasis>
lophate, radially symmetrical, smooth (Suessy &amp; Urtubey 2007). 
<emphasis box="[771,1013,1310,1336]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Chromosome number</emphasis>
unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,878,1949]" box="[189,362,1346,1372]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,362,1346,1372]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<figureCitation box="[189,302,1346,1372]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="24.[136,229,1297,1319]" captionTargetBox="[155,1431,397,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-94@24.[151,1436,389,1273]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 8. Fulcaldea and Huarpea. A: Fulcaldea. B–E: Huarpea. A: Fulcaldea stuessyi. Inflorescence with a white arrow showing swollen style below the branching point. B: Huarpea andina. Habit. C: Capitulum showing five ray flowers and a disc flower. D: Lateral view from the capitula. E: Dissected capitula showing three ray flowers (white) and a disc flower (yellow). Photos by Ivan Abreu (A) and Darwinion Institute (B–E)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5453931" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5453931/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Fig. 8b–e</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[315,357,1346,1372]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="28.[136,229,1992,2014]" captionTargetBox="[304,1284,215,1946]" captionTargetId="figure-21@28.[290,1297,190,1968]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 10. Geographical distribution for the genera of Barnadesioideae. A: Dasyphyllum. B: Chuquiraga. C: Barnadesia (red dots) and Huarpea (blue triangle). D: Doniophyton (blue triangles); E: Archidasyphyllum (blue triangles); Fulcaldea (blue triangles)—these words (triagle) in plural (triangles)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5453935" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5453935/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">10c</figureCitation>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="134" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,878,1949]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,493,1382,1408]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Distribution and habitat:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cabrera" authorityYear="1951" box="[521,621,1383,1408]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Huarpea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[521,621,1383,1408]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Huarpea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a monotypic genus restricted to the department of Iglesia in 
<collectingRegion country="Argentina" name="San Juan" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">San Juan province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[250,361,1418,1444]" name="Argentina" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cabrera, A. L." box="[380,541,1418,1445]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="129 - 132" refId="ref28784" refString="Cabrera, A. L. (1951) Huarpea, nuevo genero de Compuestas. Boletin de la Sociedad Argentina de Botanica 4: 129 - 132." type="journal article" year="1951">Cabrera 1951</bibRefCitation>
). The sole species, 
<taxonomicName box="[772,888,1418,1444]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Huarpea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andina">
<emphasis box="[772,888,1418,1444]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">H. andina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is found in the dry Monte vegetation above an altitude of 
<quantity box="[257,349,1454,1481]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" unit="m" value="3300.0">3,300 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Stuessy, T. F. &amp; Sang, T. &amp; DeVore, M. L." box="[364,581,1454,1481]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="463 - 490" refId="ref31987" refString="Stuessy, T. F., Sang, T. &amp; DeVore, M. L. (1996) Phylogeny and biogeography of the subfamily Barnadesioideae with implications for early evolution of the Compositae. In: Hind, D. J. H. &amp; Beentje, H. J. (Eds.) Compositae: Systematics. Proceedings of the International Compositae Conference, Kew, 1994, vol. 1. Royal Botanical Garden, Kew, pp. 463 - 490." type="book chapter" year="1996">
Stuessy 
<emphasis box="[458,514,1454,1480]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">et al.</emphasis>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,878,1949]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,265,1490,1516]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Notes:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cabrera" authorityYear="1951" box="[294,394,1491,1516]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Huarpea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[294,394,1491,1516]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Huarpea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Bremer &amp; R. K. Jansen (Bremer &amp; Jansen" authorityYear="1992" baseAuthorityName="D. Don" box="[813,998,1490,1516]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="141" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Barnadesioideae">Barnadesioideae</taxonomicName>
genera by being unarmed subshrubs up to 
<quantity box="[164,240,1526,1553]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" unit="cm" value="4.5">4.5 cm</quantity>
tall, capitula hidden by the leaves, with 5 ray flowers, hermaphroditic and subbilabiate corollas and one-disc flower with tubular corollas and atrophied gynoecium (
<bibRefCitation author="Cabrera, A. L." box="[751,907,1562,1589]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="129 - 132" refId="ref28784" refString="Cabrera, A. L. (1951) Huarpea, nuevo genero de Compuestas. Boletin de la Sociedad Argentina de Botanica 4: 129 - 132." type="journal article" year="1951">Cabrera 1951</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Stuessy, T. F. &amp; Urtubey, E. &amp; Gruenstaeudl, M." box="[918,1134,1562,1588]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="215 - 228" refId="ref32076" refString="Stuessy, T. F., Urtubey, E. &amp; Gruenstaeudl, M. (2009) Barnadesieae (Barnadesioideae). In: Funk, V. A., Susanna, A., Stuessy, T. &amp; Bayer, R. J. (Eds.) Systematics, evolution, and biogeography of Compositae. IAPT, Vienna, pp. 215 - 228." type="book chapter" year="2009">
Stuessy 
<emphasis box="[1011,1066,1562,1588]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
). Phylogenetically, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cabrera" authorityYear="1951" box="[1352,1452,1563,1588]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Huarpea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1352,1452,1563,1588]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Huarpea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is always recovered as sister to 
<taxonomicName box="[486,615,1598,1624]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Barnadesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[486,615,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Barnadesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bremer, K." box="[628,780,1598,1624]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" refId="ref28720" refString="Bremer, K. (1994) Asteraceae: cladistics and classification. Timber Press, Portland, 752 pp." type="book" year="1994">Bremer 1994</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Stuessy, T. F. &amp; Sang, T. &amp; DeVore, M. L." box="[790,1003,1598,1624]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="463 - 490" refId="ref31987" refString="Stuessy, T. F., Sang, T. &amp; DeVore, M. L. (1996) Phylogeny and biogeography of the subfamily Barnadesioideae with implications for early evolution of the Compositae. In: Hind, D. J. H. &amp; Beentje, H. J. (Eds.) Compositae: Systematics. Proceedings of the International Compositae Conference, Kew, 1994, vol. 1. Royal Botanical Garden, Kew, pp. 463 - 490." type="book chapter" year="1996">
Stuessy 
<emphasis box="[882,938,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">et al.</emphasis>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gustafsson, M. H. G. &amp; Pepper, A. S. R. &amp; Albert, V. A. &amp; Kallersjo, M." box="[1013,1265,1598,1624]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="149 - 160" refId="ref29823" refString="Gustafsson, M. H. G., Pepper, A. S. R., Albert, V. A. &amp; Kallersjo, M. (2001) Molecular phylogeny of the Barnadesioideae (Asteraceae). Nordic Journal of Botany 21: 149 - 160. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1756 - 1051.2001. tb 01352. x" type="journal article" year="2001">
Gustafsson 
<emphasis box="[1144,1200,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gruenstaeudl, M. &amp; Urtubey, E. &amp; Jansen, R. K. &amp; Samuel, R. &amp; Barfuss, M. H. J. &amp; Stuessy, T. F." pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="572 - 587" refId="ref29745" refString="Gruenstaeudl, M., Urtubey, E., Jansen, R. K., Samuel, R., Barfuss, M. H. J. &amp; Stuessy, T. F. (2009) Phylogeny of Barnadesioideae (Asteraceae) inferred from DNA sequence data and morphology. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 51: 572 - 587. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2009.01.023" type="journal article" year="2009">
Gruenstaeudl 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">et al.</emphasis>
2009
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Ferreira, P. L. &amp; Saavedra, M. M. &amp; Groppo, M." box="[243,464,1634,1660]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="6475" refId="ref29409" refString="Ferreira, P. L., Saavedra, M. M. &amp; Groppo, M. (2019) Phylogeny and circumscription of Dasyphyllum (Asteraceae: Barnadesioideae) based on molecular data with the recognition of a new genus, Archidasyphyllum. PeerJ 7: e 6475. https: // doi. org / 10.7717 / peerj. 6475" type="journal article" year="2019">
Ferreira 
<emphasis box="[339,396,1634,1660]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">et al.</emphasis>
2019
</bibRefCitation>
). This clade is distinguished by the radiate and heterogamous capitula, slightly sagittate or decurrent anther bases, lophate pollen, and atrophied gynoecium in the disc flowers (only in 
<taxonomicName box="[1211,1340,1670,1696]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Barnadesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1211,1340,1670,1696]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Barnadesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[136,226,1707,1732]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Barnadesia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Bacasia">
<emphasis box="[136,226,1707,1732]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Bacasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[136,1452,878,1949]" box="[189,557,1742,1769]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,351,1742,1768]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134">Iconography:</emphasis>
— 
<bibRefCitation author="Cabrera, A. L." box="[379,553,1742,1769]" pageId="25" pageNumber="134" pagination="129 - 132" refId="ref28784" refString="Cabrera, A. L. (1951) Huarpea, nuevo genero de Compuestas. Boletin de la Sociedad Argentina de Botanica 4: 129 - 132." type="journal article" year="1951">Cabrera (1951)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
